CREATE TABLE alignment
(
    id        INTEGER not null
            primary key,
    alignment TEXT default NULL
);
CREATE TABLE attribute
(
    id             INTEGER not null

);
CREATE TABLE colour

);

);

);
CREATE TABLE race
(
    id   INTEGER not null
            primary key,
    race TEXT default NULL
);
CREATE TABLE superhero
(
    id             INTEGER not null
            primary key,
    superhero_name TEXT default NULL,
    full_name      TEXT default NULL,
    gender_id      INTEGER          default NULL,
    eye_colour_id  INTEGER          default NULL,
    hair_colour_id INTEGER          default NULL,
    skin_colour_id INTEGER          default NULL,

    height_cm      INTEGER          default NULL,
    weight_kg      INTEGER          default NULL,
    foreign key (alignment_id) references alignment(id),
    foreign key (eye_colour_id) references colour(id),
    foreign key (gender_id) references gender(id),
    foreign key (hair_colour_id) references colour(id),

    foreign key (skin_colour_id) references colour(id)
);
CREATE TABLE hero_attribute
(

CREATE TABLE hero_power
(

    foreign key (hero_id) references superhero(id),
    foreign key (power_id) references superpower(id)
);

content.text:
The database schema has no column or table related to the era or time period when a superhero was created (e.g., "Silver Age of Comics"). There is no publication date, creation year, or era field in any table.

The claim references the "Silver Age of Comics" — a concept about when superheroes were originally created. This information is simply not present in the database schema. The database tracks superhero attributes like name, gender, alignment, physical characteristics, powers, and publisher, but has no temporal/chronological data about when characters were created.

This is an **OUT-OF-SCHEMA** situation — the claim cannot be verified because the database lacks information about the era or time period of character creation.
